Why are Mercedes so slow? Defending F1 champions say Bahrain GP pace issues caused by parts shortages and drag The Bahrain GP saw Ferrari and Red Bull far ahead of Mercedes in terms of pace BAHRAIN, BAHRAIN - MARCH 20: Third placed Lewis Hamilton of Great Britain and Mercedes looks on in parc ferme during the F1 Grand Prix of Bahrain at Bahrain International Circuit on March 20, 2022 in Bahrain, Bahrain. (Photo by Dan Istitene - Formula 1/Formula 1 via Getty Images) Hamilton celebrated third but it was far from the high standards of Mercedes in previous years (Photo: Getty) author avatar image By Kevin Garside Chief Sports Correspondent March 21, 2022 7:00 am(Updated 9:53 am) BAHRAIN — Too much drag and too little power. Apart from that Mercedes head to Saudi Arabia this week full of beans.
The mood in Bahrain was one of immense relief after a chastening weekend that showed Mercedes to be a long way off the pace of Ferrari and Red Bull.
In the circumstances, third for Lewis Hamilton and fourth for George Russell felt like a lottery win. And they know Red Bull won’t be posting double DNFs every week.

The problems are both aerodynamic and engine-based. The car has to run too high off the ground to offset the problems with porpoising or bouncing at high speeds. This in turn affects the car’s ability to punch a clean hole through the air, creating excessive drag and lack of grip.

No team cranks out the upgrades like Mercedes but even they can’t cut the gap in the space of seven days, as team principal Toto Wolff acknowledged.
“I think with the soft tyre, on pure pace before the tyre degrades, we are almost there. Not where Leclerc (Ferrari) is but with the others. The degradation is too big,” Wolff said.
“We tried to do something different by putting the hard tyre on but it was a second slower every single lap, so lesson learned.
“We had too much drag and that is just because we are lacking parts at the moment. Hopefully we can remedy that, and make progress on the top two’s advantage.

“At the moment we are fifth and sixth on the track, and we are trying to recover ground but it is not going to come from one day to the other. We’ll keep pushing.”
Engineering director Andrew Shovlin echoed that sentiment. “The gaps are pretty big but we can see so much performance that we can bring. The car has been reliable.
“We have a lot of ideas to explore to improve our pace and we’ll be working hard over the next few days and weeks to bring those to the track.”
What of the two men who actually have to drive the thing? Hamilton celebrated exuberantly in the cockpit when crossing the line to secure third but Russell, whose fourth-place finish was a career best, was a little less optimistic.
“Considering how difficult the car is to drive at the moment, it really wasn’t too bad, but we’re here to win,” Russell said.
“I don’t think we’re going to find the silver bullet soon. But I have faith that we will find it [but] I think it’s going be a good couple of races before we really start unlocking some more performance from the car.”
